“Last year, we lost 3,362 people through road accidents compared to 3,676 by November this year.
“Majority of these accidents are as result of speeding, alcohol influence, disregard of road signs among other human causes,” said Mr Kitur.
Speaking in Eldoret during a crackdown at Cheptiret junction along the Eldoret-Nakuru highway, Mr Kitur said the death toll is likely to increase during Christmas and New Year festivities.
During the crackdown, several unroadworthy vehicles were impounded.
He said there is need to educate boda boda riders on road safety to avert more accidents during this festive season.
He expressed fear that if all stakeholders do not work together, we’ll continue to needlessly lose people in road accidents
“As police and NTSA, we are working together to minimise accidents on our roads during this festive season. We want members of the public to co-operate with us by adhering to all safety regulations,” said Mr Kitur.



